# Copy to ``backend/.env``, repo-root ``.env``, or ``%USERPROFILE%\.ai-file-sorter\.env`` (all are loaded).
#
# Legal links for the **desktop/web UI** are Vite vars in ``frontend/.env`` (not read by Python):
#   VITE_PRIVACY_POLICY_URL=https://exosites.ch/eng/app-privacy
#   VITE_TERMS_OF_SERVICE_URL=https://exosites.ch/eng/app-terms
#
# Packaged ``backend.exe`` also reads ``.env`` next to the executable.
# When the desktop app spawns the backend, also supported:
# - ``.env`` inside ``EXOSITES_USER_DATA`` (Electron userData), or
# - ``.env`` in the app ``resources/`` folder next to ``backend.exe`` (Electron sets ``EXOSITES_BACKEND_RESOURCE_DIR``).
# The backend loads one of those files automatically on startup (never commit real secrets).
# The Electron app also injects OAuth-related keys (Gmail, Infomaniak, etc.) from ``backend/.env`` (dev) or ``resources/.env`` then userData ``.env`` (packaged) into the backend child environment and Electron main so Connect flows work without manual env copying.
#
# --- Gmail (Desktop OAuth client) — simplest: two variables ---
# EXOSITES_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
# EXOSITES_GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your-secret
#
# Google Drive in the desktop app reads EXOSITES_GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID in the Electron main process.
# If you only set the two lines above, the app copies CLIENT_ID (and CLIENT_SECRET) into the main process
# so Web OAuth clients can exchange the authorization code — same pair as Gmail.
# EXOSITES_GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=your-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
#
# In Google Cloud → OAuth client → Authorized redirect URIs, add exactly:
#   http://127.0.0.1:8789/callback
# Or set both below to match what you registered (e.g. http://localhost:8789/callback).
# EXOSITES_GMAIL_OAUTH_PORT=8789
# EXOSITES_GMAIL_OAUTH_REDIRECT_URI=http://127.0.0.1:8789/callback
#
# --- Alternative: path to Google’s downloaded JSON (``installed`` client) ---
# EXOSITES_GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_JSON=C:\path\to\client_secret_....json
#
# --- Or drop JSON at (no env needed for path): ---
#   %USERPROFILE%\.ai-file-sorter\gmail_oauth_client.json
# See ``gmail_oauth_client.json.example`` in this folder.
#
# --- Packaged Electron app (optional vendor setup) ---
# Place a real Desktop client JSON at ``electron/resources/gmail_oauth_client.json`` before
# ``node scripts/package-app.js`` (file is gitignored). The app sets EXOSITES_GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_JSON
# for the backend so users only click **Connect Gmail** and approve in the browser.
# Google Cloud must still list the redirect URI (see above) and enable Gmail API.
#
# --- Staging directories and path roots ---
# The Electron main process sets EXOSITES_USER_DATA to Electron's app.getPath("userData")
# (e.g. C:\Users\<you>\AppData\Roaming\<AppName> on Windows).
# Temporary staging folders for file sorting live under that base:
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/drive_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/   — Google Drive imports
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/dropbox_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/ — Dropbox imports
# The Python backend (upload_staging.safe_staging_roots) allows both this base AND
# APP_STATE_DIR (~/.ai-file-sorter) so dev/CLI runs without Electron also work.
# If you add a new source, add its subfolder name to _STAGING_SUBDIR_NAMES in upload_staging.py
# AND to assertSafeStagingDir in electron/integrations/ipc.js — never edit just one side.
# EXOSITES_USER_DATA is injected automatically by the Electron main process; do not set it manually.
#
# --- Microsoft OneDrive (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# Register an app in Azure AD (Entra ID) → App registrations:
#   Platform: Mobile and desktop application
#   Redirect URI (must match exactly — default port 58888):
#     http://127.0.0.1:58888/callback
#   Optional: EXOSITES_MICROSOFT_OAUTH_REDIRECT_PORT=58888 if you change the port below.
#   Delegated permissions: Files.ReadWrite, User.Read, offline_access, openid, profile
#   Supported account types: "Accounts in any organizational directory and personal Microsoft accounts"
# Copy the Application (client) ID here:
# EXOSITES_MICROSOFT_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=your-azure-app-client-id
#
# Users sign in via "Connect" on the OneDrive card in External sources.
#
# Staging folder created under userData:
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/onedrive_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/ — OneDrive imports
#
# --- Dropbox (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# Create an app at https://www.dropbox.com/developers/apps (choose "Full Dropbox" or "App Folder").
# Under OAuth 2 → Redirect URIs, add http://127.0.0.1 (no port — Dropbox allows dynamic loopback ports).
# Copy the App key here:
# EXOSITES_DROPBOX_APP_KEY=your_app_key_here
#
# --- Notion (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# Create a public integration at https://www.notion.so/my-integrations
#   (Type: Public; Capabilities: Read/Update/Insert content as needed).
# Under "OAuth Domain & URIs" → Redirect URIs, add EXACTLY:
#   http://localhost:8731/callback
#   (Use localhost, not 127.0.0.1 — Notion's portal rejects a raw loopback IP and
#    auto-prepends https://. Notion also requires the exact port: it does not honor
#    port-less loopback matching.)
# Copy the OAuth Client ID and Client Secret here (Notion requires the secret for the token exchange):
# EXOSITES_NOTION_CLIENT_ID=your_notion_client_id_here
# EXOSITES_NOTION_CLIENT_SECRET=your_notion_client_secret_here
# After connecting, share the Notion pages/databases you want the assistant to use with the integration
# (open a page → ••• → Connections → add your integration).
#
# --- Amazon S3 (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# No OAuth app registration needed. Create an IAM user or role with s3:GetObject + s3:ListBucket.
# Credentials are stored locally in Electron userData (never sent to any server).
# Enter Access Key ID, Secret Access Key, Region, and Bucket via the S3 card in External sources.
#
# Staging folder created under userData:
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/s3_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/ — S3 object imports
#
# --- Slack (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# Create an app at https://api.slack.com/apps (choose "From scratch").
# Under "OAuth & Permissions" → Redirect URLs, add: http://127.0.0.1
# Under "OAuth & Permissions" → User Token Scopes, add:
#   channels:read, groups:read, im:read, mpim:read,
#   channels:history, groups:history, im:history, mpim:history,
#   chat:write, search:read, users:read, files:read
# Or use the in-app setup guide on External sources → Slack (credentials stored locally).
# Copy Client ID and Client Secret here (optional if using the setup guide):
# EXOSITES_SLACK_CLIENT_ID=your_slack_client_id_here
# EXOSITES_SLACK_CLIENT_SECRET=your_slack_client_secret_here
#
# --- iCloud Drive (desktop app — no API key needed) ---
# No registration required. Select your local iCloud Drive sync folder in External sources.
# Requires iCloud for Windows (Windows) or iCloud on macOS — files must be synced locally.
#
# Staging folder created under userData:
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/icloud_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/ — iCloud file copies
#
# --- Infomaniak kDrive (desktop app — Electron main process only) ---
# Create an app at https://manager.infomaniak.com/v3/ng/accounts/applications/list
# Under Redirect URIs, add exactly (default port 58889 — must match what the app uses):
#   http://127.0.0.1:58889/callback
# Or pick another port and set EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_OAUTH_REDIRECT_PORT to the same value here and in the Manager.
# Put Client ID (and Client secret if your app is confidential) in backend/.env — Electron syncs these into the
# main process on startup so Connect kDrive works without duplicating vars for Python vs Electron.
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_CLIENT_ID=your_infomaniak_client_id_here
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_CLIENT_SECRET=your_infomaniak_client_secret_here
# Infomaniak scopes are selected on the Manager application. Leave these unset unless Infomaniak support
# tells you to request explicit scopes; invalid scope names make the login page appear blank.
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_OAUTH_SCOPE=
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_DRIVE_OAUTH_SCOPE=
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_CALENDAR_OAUTH_SCOPE=
#
# Optional static API bearer (Electron main only — not passed to the Python backend). When set, kDrive and
# Infomaniak Calendar use this token without browser OAuth; scopes must match what you need. If both this and
# Connect are used, the env token takes precedence for API calls. Never commit real values.
# EXOSITES_INFOMANIAK_TOKEN=
#
# Staging folder created under userData:
#   {EXOSITES_USER_DATA}/infomaniak_sort_staging/<hex-job-id>/ — kDrive imports
#
# --- Crash reports → central ingest API (optional; backend only — never VITE_ / frontend) ---
# Crash rows are forwarded to the account API (api.exosites.ch), which owns the DB
# credentials. When URL and token are both set, the backend exposes
# crash_reports_ingest_enabled on GET /v1/public/client-config and accepts POST /v1/crash-reports.
# EXOSITES_CRASH_INGEST_URL=https://api.exosites.ch/v1/crash-reports
# EXOSITES_CRASH_INGEST_TOKEN=the-same-value-as-CRASH_INGEST_TOKEN-on-the-node-api
# Verify TLS (default 1). Set 0 only for local dev against a non-TLS endpoint.
# EXOSITES_CRASH_INGEST_SSL=1
# Request timeout in seconds (default 15).
# EXOSITES_CRASH_INGEST_TIMEOUT=15
# Set to 1 in pytest/CI to block forwarding even when URL/token are present:
# EXOSITES_CRASH_INGEST_DISABLED=1
#
# --- Classification (optional) ---
# Below this extraction-quality score → Uncertain unless trust rules apply (default 0.28).
# EXTRACTION_UNCERTAIN_QUALITY=0.28
#
# --- Spreadsheet preview (xlsx/xls/csv text for sorting) ---
# EXOSITES_SPREADSHEET_PREVIEW_MAX_ROWS=50
# EXOSITES_SPREADSHEET_PREVIEW_MAX_SHEETS=3
#
# --- Video sorting ---
# ffmpeg/ffprobe: set explicit paths, put them on PATH, or place a build under repo ``tools/ffmpeg/<name>/bin/``
# (the backend auto-discovers that tree when PATH is empty). GET /meta/video shows what resolved.
# ``tools/ffmpeg/`` is often gitignored (large binaries) — unpack locally or rely on PATH in CI.
# EXOSITES_FFMPEG_PATH=C:\path\to\ffmpeg.exe
# EXOSITES_FFPROBE_PATH=C:\path\to\ffprobe.exe
# Stronger filing signal: longer cap + more of the clip for frames + STT (optional).
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_MAX_DURATION_SEC=900
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_MAX_EXTRACT_SEC=180
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_FRAME_COUNT=3
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_MAX_TRANSCRIPT_CHARS=4000
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_FFPROBE_TIMEOUT_SEC=60
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_FFMPEG_TIMEOUT_SEC=180
# Optional transcript (also: pip install -r backend/requirements-video.txt)
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_STT_ENABLE=1
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_STT_MODEL=base
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_STT_DEVICE=cpu
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_STT_COMPUTE_TYPE=int8
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_STT_LANGUAGE=
# Optional: add QuickTime author tag into filing text (may be PII)
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_METADATA_INCLUDE_AUTHOR=0
# Diagnostic logs for video extraction + gate decisions
# EXOSITES_VIDEO_DEBUG_LOG=1
#
# --- Ollama: cloud inference only (Exo VPS / LiteLLM) ---
# All sort/classify/embed/vision LLM calls go to OLLAMA_HOST — never local ``ollama serve``.
# See docs/CLOUD_LLM_ONLY.md. Local mode (OLLAMA_MODE=local) is pytest-only.
OLLAMA_MODE=remote
EXOSITES_REMOTE_LLM=1
OLLAMA_HOST=https://llm-staging.exosites.ch
# Do not set OLLAMA_API_KEY when signed into Exo cloud — the desktop app injects a short-lived virtual key.
# OLLAMA_API_KEY=sk-litellm-virtual-key
# OLLAMA_REQUEST_TIMEOUT_S=120
# OLLAMA_MAX_RETRIES=3
# EXOSITES_LLM_MAX_SLOTS=4
# Optional VPS Redis queue for classify/embed (set automatically when SORT_LLM_QUEUE_ENABLED=1).
# EXOSITES_SORT_QUEUE_URL=https://llm-staging.exosites.ch
# Max seconds to wait for an LLM slot when slots are configured (remote/cloud).
# EXOSITES_LLM_SLOT_WAIT_S=600
#
# --- Cloud sort worker (OCR + full analyze on VPS) ---
# Set automatically on sign-in when broker returns sort_service_mode=cloud_full.
# EXOSITES_CLOUD_SORT_WORKER=1
# EXOSITES_CLOUD_SORT_WORKER_URL=https://llm-staging.exosites.ch/v1/sort/worker
# EXOSITES_SORT_SERVICE_MODE=cloud_full
# EXOSITES_CLOUD_SORT_WORKER_TIMEOUT_S=600
#
# --- Ollama performance (VPS ops — not desktop) ---
# Number of CPU threads on the inference VPS. Do not set on end-user desktops.
# OLLAMA_NUM_THREADS=8
#
# --- Sort throughput (optional) ---
# Second LLM call before classification (per file). Set 0 for faster runs when quality tradeoff is OK.
# DOCUMENT_BRIEFING_ENABLE=1
# Skip briefing for short, high-quality plaintext extracts (reduces LLM rounds on obvious .txt).
# DOCUMENT_BRIEFING_SKIP_SMALL_TEXT_ENABLE=1
# BRIEFING_SKIP_MAX_TEXT_CHARS=10000
# Larger cap for Gmail-exported message bodies (headers + body often exceed the generic cap).
# BRIEFING_SKIP_GMAIL_MESSAGE_MAX_TEXT_CHARS=24000
# BRIEFING_SKIP_MIN_QUALITY=0.42
# Semantic rerank (VPS embeddings via LiteLLM). Ops: provision nomic-embed-text on the LLM stack.
# SEMANTIC_RERANK=1
# SEMANTIC_RERANK_MODEL=nomic-embed-text
# Narrow rerank tie-break: extra LLM when top-2 scores are very close (lower = fewer extra calls, less accuracy).
# OLLAMA_NARROW_MARGIN=0.06
#
# Parallel analyze tasks: batch folder jobs AND Gmail/Drive streaming import (overlap local read + classify).
# Default 1 (safe). Clamped 1–8. Raises GPU/RAM and Ollama load — confirm GPU use before increasing.
# EXOSITES_SORT_MAX_CONCURRENCY=1
# Per-file timing logs: DEBUG line every row when 1 (raise log level so DEBUG is visible, e.g. uvicorn --log-level debug).
# INFO line when wall time ≥ threshold ms (works at default INFO; set to 0 to disable slow-row logs only).
# EXOSITES_ANALYZE_PHASE_TIMING_DEBUG_LOG=0
# EXOSITES_ANALYZE_PHASE_SLOW_LOG_MS=30000
#
# --- Gemini (Voice + Agent features) ---
# Obtain at https://aistudio.google.com/app/apikey
# Required for real-time voice and autonomous task planning.
# GEMINI_API_KEY=your-gemini-api-key-here
# GEMINI_VOICE_MODEL=models/gemini-2.5-flash-native-audio-preview-12-2025
#
# --- Assistant restructure feature flags (default ON; set =0 to disable) ---
# See docs/ASSISTANT_RESTRUCTURE_PLAN.md and docs/adr/009-012.
# ASSISTANT_PROVIDER_CONTEXT=1      # inject user chat provider into voice agent tools
# ASSISTANT_CALENDAR_SERVICE=1      # unified confirm/create/delete; =0 uses direct tool dispatch
# ASSISTANT_TURN_SERVICE=1          # echo/junk filters at turn_complete; =0 commits raw STT
# ASSISTANT_CAPABILITY_ROUTER=1     # redirect misrouted voice tools before dispatch
# ASSISTANT_UNIFIED_TURN=1          # POST /assistant/turn; =0 returns 404
# ASSISTANT_ORCHESTRATOR_TASK_QUEUE=1  # /agent/task uses orchestrator; =0 uses legacy planner
#
# --- Logging ---
# Controls Python root log level. INFO (default) shows tool lifecycle + warnings.
# Set to DEBUG to trace every automation step and action entry point.
# LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG
#
# --- Memory recall signal (second brain) ---
# EXOSITES_MEMORY_RECALL_SIGNAL=1   # recall_weight ranking, last_recalled_at, stale cleanup
# EXOSITES_MEMORY_STALE_DAYS=90     # auto-memory stale threshold when signal enabled
